{The genre of short but highly tactical battles - for which there is no clear
definition, but rather a matter of perception by the audience - was reinvented
by Daniel Keith and Martin Minski in the past few years, but it dates much
further back. This position shows one battle that could be considered that way
but is ending with stalemate, as opposed to the "open-ended" nature of those
modern studies. White is to move and has to draw, and compared to other
stalemate studies the battle here feels sharp and tactical, although not very
difficult once one sees the solution.} 1. Rd5 Bxf3 ({Less tactical feeis the
other main variation that even suffers from a minor dual:} 1... Nd4 2. Rxd4
Bxf3 3. Bc6 ({or} 3. Bd1 $11) 3... a1=Q 4. Bxf3+ Kh2 {and while the end of the
main variation shows the clearest draw, many other moves are actually possible,
as White can keep both pieces.} 5. Rd2+ Kg1 6. Rd1+ Qxd1 7. Bxd1 $11) 2. Bc6 $1
a1=Q {and now the elegant main idea follows:} 3. Rd1+ Qxd1 4. Bxf3+ Qxf3 $11
1/2-1/2

