{For the other three studies, we will look at a few prizes won by Prokes. This
study has a beautiful idea which is bought with a knight on h1 that does not
participate. Such studies with geometrical motives that repeat on a line/rank/
diagonal were in the spirit of the Soviet school, but inspired also other
composers. Back in 1949, in fact, Czechoslovakia was part of the Union,
referred to as (abbreviated) CSSR or Czechoslovakian Soviet Socialist Republic.
This, however, likely did not influence the style of our hero, as by then he
composed for over two decades and grew up with his own style. More influence
will have had that he likely saw studies with similar motifs and tried to
create one himself, regardless of their country of origin.} 1. b6+ Ka8 2. a6
Qd5 $1 {After the introduction, the maneuver begins - one that on lack of
occasion is rarely seen in games in this form, although the basic idea is
known to almost every player.} (2... bxa6 $2 3. Bxa6 $18 {The two bishops here
win easily against the knight, as either Pg3 survives or checkmate follows.})
3. Bc4 Qc6 4. Bb5 Qe4 5. Bd3 Qf3 6. Be2 Qg2 7. Bf1 1/2-1/2

