{This study shows in my opinion nice rook endgame tactics, ending in a
checkmate. White is to move and win, the top priority being saving his pawns. 
Note that the Ph5, which also is used to make White's moves unique, prevents 3.
-Rh1+ in the 1.-K:d7 variation. The Prokes maneuver in action (or rather
prevented).} 1. Rd7+ (1. g6 $2 Kf6 $1 2. Rd4 Kxg6 3. Rxf4 Kg7) 1... Ke6 $1 {
The only move if Black doesn't want to lose immediately.} (1... Kf8 2. Rd8+ Kg7
3. Rxh8 $18) (1... Kxd7 2. g6 Ke7 3. g7 Rf8 4. g8=Q Rxf7 {and now there are
likely many ways of winning, but taking Ph5 makes it pretty easy.} 5. Qg5+ $18)
2. g6 Kf6 $1 {The next move is the "star move" of this study, and it is a
motif that I have not seen in a practical game yet even though it could easily
happen.} 3. Re7 Rf8 $1 4. Re8 Kg7 {I had this or similar formations often.
White can move only his king now, Black can move neither king nor rook. In
practical games, usually there is more material on the board, making the
movable king decisive easily. Here there is only one winning way, but it is
nice.} 5. Kg2 $1 c5 6. Kh3 c4 7. Kh4 c3 8. Kg5 c2 9. Rxf8 Kxf8 10. Kf6 c1=Q 11.
g7# 1-0

