{Of course this study from June 1939, showing the Prokes maneuver, had to be
added as a bonus. I would not feel comfortable with it taking a main spot, as
it is famous and reproduced "everywhere". Black has two strong pawns, and
White wants to draw.} 1. Kg4 e2 $1 ({The first other main variation is without
the maneuver:} 1... d2 2. Kf3 Kd3 3. Ra1 $1 e2 4. Ra3+ Kc2 5. Ra2+ Kc1 6. Ra1+
Kb2 7. Kxe2 $11) 2. Rc1+ Kd4 ({The other main variations add not much:} 2...
Kb3 3. Kf3 d2 4. Rb1+ Kc2 5. Kxe2 $11) ({this one at least repeats the
maneuver.} 2... Kd5 3. Kf3 d2 4. Rc5+ $1 Kxc5 5. Kxe2 $11) 3. Kf3 $1 d2 {Here
the main point comes in: White is to move, but how can he draw? Well, he must
get rid of his rook, as then Pd2 can't capture anymore.} 4. Rc4+ $1 Kd3 $1 5.
Rd4+ $1 Kxd4 6. Kxe2 Kc3 7. Kd1 Kd3 1/2-1/2

