{This study can serve to illustrate how one theme can evolve into another.
There is nothing to be seen anymore of the original idea of our hero, rather
Ionchev's setting was taken but new play added. Sadly the position is heavy
and crowded. White is to move and win, for which his advanced pawn is the only
hope. I won't bore readers with the support variations, and instead almost
only give the main line.} 1. Bc2 $1 Qxa1 ({The strength of the advanced pawn
is shown in this and the next side variation:} 1... b2 2. Rxc1 bxc1=Q 3. Qd1
Qxd1 (3... a3 4. d7 Qf4 5. Bxg6 $1 $18) 4. Bxd1 a3 5. d7 c2 6. d8=N $1 cxd1=Q
7. Nf7#) 2. Bd1 c2 $1 3. Qxa1 b2 {Ionchev's position is reached in the corner,
but with the additional material White has an ace up his sleeve. A queen dance
follows, motivated by check- and stalemate.} 4. d7 $1 c1=Q $1 (4... bxa1=Q 5.
d8=N $1 cxd1=Q 6. Nf7#) 5. Qb1 $1 (5. d8=N $2 Qc7 $1 6. Qb1 Qxd8 7. Bxf3 Qc7 $1
8. Qh1 b1=Q 9. Qxb1 a3 10. Kg2 Qc1 $1 11. Qxc1 $11) 5... a3 $1 (5... Qxb1 6.
d8=N $1 Qf5 7. gxf5 b1=Q 8. Nf7+ Kh5 9. Bxf3+ g4+ 10. Bxg4#) 6. d8=N $1 Qf4 7.
Qe4 $1 Qf8 8. Qe1 $1 b1=Q 9. Qh1 Qxd1 10. Qh2 $1 {Now both players have two
pieces, but the mate threats can't be prevented for the materially stronger
side.} (10. Qxd1 $2 Qf4 11. Qh1 Qh2+ $1 12. Qxh2 $11) 10... Qf4 11. Nf7+ $1
Qxf7 12. Kg3# {For many years, I wanted to do something with Ionchev's setting,
thanks to the Hungarian master Rusz, who lately worked on the Grip theme and
"mined" incredible zugzwangs from the Lomonossov/Syzygy bases, it became
possible. The study might not be to the taste of everyone, and I was actually
surprised it won the informal tourney.} 1-0

